### How to Create an Engaging Engineering CTF Competition

Building Capture The Flag competitions and generating questions

### About CTF

Capture The Flag, abbreviated as CTF, is a sport that originated in the West and is commonly seen in paintball and first-person shooter games today. The original concept involves teams competing to protect their own flag from being taken while also trying to capture the flags of other teams. In the computer field, this translates to "attack and defense" where teams first identify their vulnerabilities to protect against intrusions, while simultaneously launching zero-latency attacks to score points by capturing from other teams.

The above describes a standard, or even "advanced," way of conducting a CTF competition. However, running a CTF competition within a company involves additional practical considerations:
1. The purpose of holding a CTF competition is not only to enhance technical skills but also to **promote communication among engineers**.
2. Engineers have different strengths, including Front-End, Back-End, APP, and DevOps; to ensure everyone can participate, the questions should not be too focused on a specific area (e.g., networking, PHP).
3. Teams should be balanced in terms of strengths and expertise across different fields.
4. The event should last no more than an afternoon.
5. Organizing a CTF competition is a side project outside of primary work responsibilities, so there are limited resources and time available.

Considering these factors, rather than calling it a CTF competition, it might be better described as:

> **_An activity for team-based puzzle-solving to accumulate flag points & promote communication among engineers_**

This is a beginner-level CTF competition!

### Activity Goals
1. Enhance engineering technical skills.
2. Promote communication among engineers.
3. Inspire enthusiasm and sharpness in exploring new things.
4. Make it fun; doing boring things can be quite painful.

Points 3 and 4 are my personal additions. My expectations for this activity go beyond practical aspects; I hope to enhance everyone's enthusiasm for exploration and learning new things in an enjoyable way, just like in daily work. We shouldn't just be code monkeys; we should find ways to break through and keep moving forward!

### Competition Rules
1. Engineers will be grouped based on their expertise and strengths.
2. Competition duration: 90 minutes.
3. A total of 12 questions will be provided, with 3 opportunities to purchase hints using earned points.
4. The cost of hints decreases over time (the earlier you buy, the more expensive it is).
5. Each question has a base score + time score (the earlier it's solved, the more points).
6. Once a team selects a question to answer, they will be locked into answering that question or any other already unlocked questions until the question is either solved or the time limit expires. (This rule is in place to encourage team members to communicate and brainstorm together rather than dividing the work).
7. The score for each question, hint cost, and lock time varies based on the difficulty of the question.
8. Victory condition: The team with the highest accumulated score wins; if scores are tied, the time taken to solve the questions will be compared.
9. The winning team receives a cash prize.

### How to Create It?

Once the activity rules and goals are clarified, the next main task is how to set up a CTF competition.

This part will be divided into two sections: **First, creating a system to conduct the CTF competition**, **Second, generating the competition questions**.

#### 1. Creating a System to Conduct the CTF Competition

> _This part requires both front-end and back-end technical skills to implement. If you're not familiar, you may need to ask other colleagues for help._

Front-end: [Semantic UI](https://semantic-ui.com/){:target="_blank"}

Back-end: PHP + JSON files for data storage.

Due to time constraints, the competition system will be built to be simple, stable, and quick. The front-end interface will directly use the [Semantic UI](https://semantic-ui.com/){:target="_blank"} framework, while the back-end will be written in PHP without using a framework, and data will be stored in JSON files without a database. Keeping it simple helps avoid issues (e.g., if someone tries to attack the competition system to directly obtain answers).

**Back-end and other logic:** The question list page will use Ajax to request the current answering status from the back-end every second. The back-end will read and record the answering status in each team's JSON file; when unlocking a question, it will record the time, and until the time is up, no other questions can be unlocked. The completion time, time score, and hint price will increase or decrease based on the time spent.

> _This is the general outline of the competition system, but the focus is not on the competition system itself, but on the questions!_

> _Whether they are interesting, whether everyone can participate, whether they have logic, whether they are novel... it's really challenging to come up with them._

Let's get to the main point!

#### **2. Generating Competition Questions**

First, let me introduce the 5 questions I came up with.

**1. The Door to the Magic Academy**

![](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*FYUNxW5IE7ZAWkoCtiQ-aw.png)

**Question Description:** You will receive a string of keys and need to use this key to decipher the spell, entering it in the spell input box; there is also a verification code field that needs to be filled out before submitting the answer.

**Answer:**

![](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*wHmLeh5xuRQgJxosba50mg.png)

This question tests cybersecurity and coding issues; it utilizes a platform's encryption and decryption vulnerability interface. If all encryption and decryption on the website are done using the same method and the same key, we can exploit this weakness to unlock the encrypted content and obtain the original data!

You can see that the verification code part is `./image.php?token=AD0HbwdgVDw=` which provides a decryption interface, so we can try using the above encryption key:

![](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*yMnbduFy0uhjh3FRPdv7sA.png)

This gives us the decrypted string: LiveALifeYouWillRemember.

Entering this into the spell input box will allow you to pass!

**2. Take Me Back to Shanghai in 1937!**

![](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*LdK9mx_sHGSs3uUYnRrqRg.png)

**Question Description:** You need to input a year/month/day to send to the back-end, allowing it to determine that it is the year 1937; the year input range (1947-2099) does not allow direct input of 1937.

**Answer:**

The main point of this question is not how to bypass the front-end check, as the back-end processes it, making it impossible to bypass; the main focus is on the [32-bit computer 2038 problem](https://zh.wikipedia.org/wiki/2038%E5%B9%B4%E9%97%AE%E9%A2%98){:target="_blank"}. Due to the 32-bit timestamp limitation, it can only display up to January 19, 2038, at 03:14:07; exceeding this will overflow back to January 1, 1901. Therefore, by calculating forward, inputting `2073-02-06 to 2074-02-05` will fall within the year 1937, and submitting a date within this range will succeed!

![[Wikipedia](https://zh.wikipedia.org/wiki/2038%E5%B9%B4%E9%97%AE%E9%A2%98#/media/File:Year_2038_problem.gif){:target="_blank"}](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*k2-G9NVw7p1HhIfSdruZtg.gif)

[Wikipedia](https://zh.wikipedia.org/wiki/2038%E5%B9%B4%E9%97%AE%E9%A2%98#/media/File:Year_2038_problem.gif){:target="_blank"}

**3. Clash of the Titans**

![](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*8FPAXgW_16rIfhbNYVmCaQ.png)

**Question Description:** You need to find a way to receive a password reset email from a third party (an email you cannot log into) and complete the password reset for someone else.

**Answer:**

This question requires more sharpness. First, use your own email to request a password reset; the email we receive is as follows:
```plaintext
Your password reset link: http://ctf.zhgchg.li/10/reset.php?requestid=OTk= If this is not related to you, please disregard this email, thank you!
```

We can see that the password reset request is identified by the `requestid` parameter, and the value we received is `OTk=`, which looks like base64? Let's give it a try:

![[base64 decode and encode](https://www.base64decode.org/){:target="_blank"}](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*RlZ9yo5KKrzVm5p5DNI3XA.png)

[base64 decode and encode](https://www.base64decode.org/){:target="_blank"}

We find that the parameter value is 99. By requesting the password reset again, we get 100, so we can infer that the password reset requests are sequential numbers, and the next number would be 101. Now, we can return to the original email we wanted to bypass and request a password reset, allowing us to forge a password reset link and secretly reset someone else's password.

![](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*Qb9ABwqE53QzSBeiXQdFBw.png)

Encoding 101 in Base64 gives us MTAx, forging the URL: `http://ctf.zhgchg.li/10/reset.php?requestid=MTAx`, entering any password and clicking reset will allow you to pass!

![](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*n3aFQLWbzmUUtrBp1L1pEw.png)

**4. Master of Disguise**

![](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*zjPlC6WZgQmIYymEodTKBg.png)

**Question Description:** You need to create 10 Gmail accounts (Gmail hosted accounts) to receive the answer emails.

**Answer:**

This question can certainly be brute-forced, but company emails cannot be registered freely; unless you find 10 people to help you receive emails, you won't be able to answer.

The key to this question is Gmail accounts/Gmail hosted accounts. Since company emails are Gmail hosted accounts, they also have the characteristics of Gmail accounts: you can use “.” and “+” to create infinite variations of the email. The “.” can be placed anywhere in the username, and “+” can be placed at the end followed by any number.

For example, if the main email is `zhgchgli@gmail.com`, then z.hgchgli@gmail.com, zh.gchgli@gmail.com, zhgchgli+1@gmail.com, zhgchgli+25@gmail.com… will all be sent to `zhgchgli@gmail.com`. One email can create multiple identities!

This question serves as a reminder to filter out these characters when registering accounts to prevent malicious users from creating numerous fake accounts.

![](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*WwYS4pVjDAMBdoJlgEr60w.png)

After receiving 10 emails, you can combine them to find the answer URL, and entering that URL will allow you to pass!

**5. Time Machine**

![](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*W21HYA96lFRydYUpAB3EPQ.png)

**Question Description:** Similar to question 3, you need to find a way to receive a verification code (4 digits) via SMS from a third party (an SMS you cannot receive) to log into someone else's account.

**Answer:**

This question is a bit more obscure and difficult, primarily simulating a side-channel timing attack. The system login verification includes a complex algorithm, and when processing verification information, timing discrepancies may occur (for example, inputting one correct digit takes longer to process, while all incorrect digits return immediately). By observing these timing discrepancies, we start from `0000` and try one digit at a time. When we try `2000`, we notice it takes one second, indicating the first digit is `2`. Continuing to try `2100` also takes one second, while `2200` takes longer, increasing to two seconds… Continuing this process for the third and fourth digits, we ultimately obtain the answer: `2256`.

This question merely simulates such an attack; the back-end processing uses sleep to simulate timing without an actual complex algorithm. Generally, in web and app environments, such attacks are rare; on one hand, the information processing is not complex enough to show significant timing discrepancies, and on the other hand, network factors can influence the results, making it difficult to judge.

For more details on side-channel attacks, you can refer to this article:

![[Understanding CORB in 30 Minutes — Side-Channel Attacks](https://segmentfault.com/a/1190000016126079){:target="_blank"}](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*SF1S_RZNTI-5ZaC3Kw1Ypw.png)

```markdown
[30 Minutes to Understand What CORB Is — Side-Channel Attacks](https://segmentfault.com/a/1190000016126079){:target="_blank"}

**1\. Sadako Appears**

![Sadako image sourced from the internet](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*I4jlrpa3w-HmqCtuTY11ig.png)

Sadako image sourced from the internet

**Question Description:** The question consists of a Sadako image. You need to enter what Sadako wants to say in the input box above to pass.

**Answer:**

This question tests whether you understand the concept that images can contain other information. The key lies in the original image:

![Sadako image sourced from the internet](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*zMmNz4PsgipRaxIPhUhYcQ.png)

Sadako image sourced from the internet

This image has secretly compressed a text file inside it (for the actual method, please refer to: [How To Hide A ZIP File Inside An Image On Mac \[Quicktip\]](https://www.hongkiat.com/blog/hide-zip-image-mac/){:target="_blank"}; note the differences between Win/Mac).

So, we just need to simply unzip this image using Commone to obtain the passphrase:

![](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*e6j1AJPcv_qROUX4xUsJHA.png)

![](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*YVOGsdi1hS2OO6ctHc6dFg.png)

**Supplement:**

Regarding the part about hiding information in images, there is another method using [Image Steganography](https://blog.trendmicro.com.tw/?p=12510){:target="_blank"}.

![[Image Steganography and Malware: Principles and Methods](https://blog.trendmicro.com.tw/?p=12510){:target="_blank"}](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*WfSUbQXSjTOg28ZWsihMHg.png)

[Image Steganography and Malware: Principles and Methods](https://blog.trendmicro.com.tw/?p=12510){:target="_blank"}

**2\. Caesar's Morse Code**

![Material image sourced from the internet](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*PZz3sUOhaUNKRmNS_jY1RA.png)

Material image sourced from the internet

**Question Description:** Try to decipher the meaning contained in the provided Morse code (a sentence in English).

**Answer:**

This question is quite straightforward. The first step is to decode the Morse code into English letters: "`VYYXI DN HT GDAZ`".

![[Morse Code Translator](https://mathsking.net/morse.htm){:target="_blank"}](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*venMZ3lkF-hYarWe9bMd6A.png)

[Morse Code Translator](https://mathsking.net/morse.htm){:target="_blank"}

Then, we perform a Caesar cipher decryption. When we try an offset of 5, we get a meaningful English sentence: "[addcn](https://www.addcn.com/){:target="_blank"} is my life," which is the answer!

![[Caesar Cipher Decryption Tool](http://ctf.ssleye.com/caesar.html){:target="_blank"}](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*kTiosisv3i7Ib9v25AYftg.png)
```

```markdown
### Summary

The competition system took about a week to build, and the questions took about three months to gradually piece together (inspiration was needed); the competition has concluded successfully, and the feedback has been quite good—"fun and interesting"; this was also my original intention, hoping everyone explores and brainstorms from a fun perspective; therefore, whether it's the question titles (which are all movie-related) or the direction of the questions, there won't be anything too deep in engineering or calculations, as that would be too dull and uninteresting!

Additionally, here is the question response rate, serving as a reference for difficulty:

![](/assets/729d7b6817a4/1*-ViR_TfrzhANOFymo1eVoA.png)

When I was creating the questions, my biggest fear was that they would be too simple and everyone would solve them quickly, or too difficult and everyone would get stuck—both situations are quite awkward.

The actual results of the questions in the competition (competition time: 90 minutes) met our expectations, just right! Not too difficult or too easy; the first-place team solved 9 questions, and even the last-place team solved 7 questions; very close, but due to time scoring and purchased hints, the final rankings were still determined!

> Surprisingly, no one managed to solve the door to the magic academy… QQ

This concludes the summary of the engineering CTF competition.
```
